    <!-- ============================================================
         CATEGORY 3: PROBE TOOLS
    ============================================================= -->
    <section class="card armory-category">
      <h2 id="probes">Probe Tools</h2>
      <p class="category-intro">Before you set a single trap, you need to find the main tunnel run — and for that, you need a probe. I've been using the same piece of rebar I found on the ground when I was 15. Still use it today. You push it into the soil a few inches out from the mound, work in a semicircle, and when it drops, you've found the tunnel. That's it.</p>
      <p class="category-intro">A plain piece of rebar from any hardware store does exactly the same job. You don't need to buy anything special. But if you want something with a real handle and a better grip — something that doesn't tear up your palm after a long day of probing — there are purpose-built gopher probes made for this exact task. I won't pretend the ergonomics aren't nicer.</p>
      <p class="category-intro">Don't want to spend anything? A piece of rebar from any hardware store does the exact same job. That's what I used for years.</p>
      <p class="category-intro">Already have an underground bait station applicator tube? That works as a probe in a pinch — same idea, just push it into the soil and feel for the drop.</p>

      <div class="field-notes">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #222;">The Bagger's Field Notes</h3>
        <p style="font-style: italic; color: #555;">"The probe is the most underrated part of the whole system. Get this step right and everything downstream is easier."</p>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          <li><strong>Probe in a semicircle</strong> 3–4 inches out from the mound edge, not directly under it. The main run is never directly below the mound.</li>
          <li><strong>Feel for the drop</strong> — when the probe suddenly sinks 2–3 inches deeper, you've hit the void. That's your set location.</li>
          <li><strong>Hard clay?</strong> Wet the area slightly before probing. Dry, compacted soil gives false positives and makes probing exhausting.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h3 class="picks-heading">Our Picks</h3>
      <div class="product-grid">

        <div class="product-card">
          <div class="product-badge badge-best">Best Overall</div>
          <h4 class="product-name">Purpose-Built Gopher Probe</h4>
          <p class="product-desc">Designed specifically for gopher work — a proper handle, calibrated tip, and the right length to reach main tunnel depth without over-penetrating. The ergonomics matter on a long session across a large yard.</p>
          <p class="product-best-for"><strong>Best for:</strong> Anyone doing regular gopher work who wants a tool that doesn't tear up their palm over dozens of probe points per session.</p>
          <a href="https://amzn.to/4dlMbrU" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="sponsored noopener">Shop on Amazon →</a>
        </div>

        <div class="product-card">
          <div class="product-badge badge-budget">Budget Pick</div>
          <h4 class="product-name">Basic Probe / Entry-Level Option</h4>
          <p class="product-desc">A functional probe that gets the job done without the premium price tag. Good for occasional use or for someone who wants to try the probing method before committing to a more serious tool. Does the same job — less comfortable over time.</p>
          <p class="product-best-for"><strong>Best for:</strong> Occasional use, smaller yards, or first-time gopher trappers getting started with the technique.</p>
          <a href="https://amzn.to/4dlMbrU" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="sponsored noopener">Shop on Amazon →</a>
        </div>

      </div>

      <h3 class="compare-heading">Quick Comparison</h3>
      <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Product</th>
              <th>Price Tier</th>
