    <!-- ============================================================
         CATEGORY 4: GOPHER MESH & HARDWARE CLOTH
    ============================================================= -->
    <section class="card armory-category">
      <h2 id="mesh">Gopher Mesh & Hardware Cloth</h2>
      <p class="category-intro">The spec matters here — go with 1/2-inch galvanized. Smaller mesh restricts root growth and starves your plants; larger mesh lets juveniles squeeze through and defeats the whole purpose. This is the permanent fix for raised beds and planting areas. I've lined dozens of beds with this stuff, and when it's installed right, it's a one-time job. The key installation detail: overlap your seams like roof shingles — water and gophers both find the same gaps.</p>
      <p class="category-intro">For a full walkthrough on installation technique, see the <a href="/methods/gopher-mesh">Gopher Mesh & Hardware Cloth guide</a>.</p>
      <a href="https://amzn.to/4b9UG87" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="sponsored noopener">Shop Gopher Mesh on Amazon →</a>
      <p class="category-guide-link">Full installation guide: <a href="/methods/gopher-mesh">Gopher Mesh & Hardware Cloth →</a></p>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         CATEGORY 5: UNDERGROUND BAIT STATIONS
    ============================================================= -->
    <section class="card armory-category">
      <h2 id="bait-stations">Underground Bait Stations</h2>
      <p class="category-intro">This is a last resort, not a first move. When I do reach for bait, I use diphacinone over zinc phosphide — it's slower acting, but it's safer to handle and carries a lower secondary poisoning risk to hawks, owls, and other things eating what you're killing. The tradeoff is worth it. I also won't use bait at all on any property where dogs are working. Full stop. If there's a dog covering that ground, we trap only.</p>
      <p class="category-intro" style="background: #fff7ed; border-left: 4px solid #f97316; padding: 0.65rem 0.9rem; border-radius: 4px; color: #92400e;"><strong>Pet safety:</strong> Never place bait stations where dogs, cats, or other animals can access them. Even tamper-resistant stations can be dug up or knocked loose. Keep pets away from treated areas until you've confirmed all stations are secure and accounted for.</p>
      <p class="category-intro">For full bait station protocol, see the <a href="/methods/poison-bait-stations">Underground Bait Stations guide</a>.</p>
      <a href="https://amzn.to/46XnfTH" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="sponsored noopener">Shop Bait Stations on Amazon →</a>
      <p class="category-guide-link">Full technique guide: <a href="/methods/poison-bait-stations">Underground Bait Stations →</a></p>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         CATEGORY 6: SONIC REPELLER STAKES
    ============================================================= -->
    <section class="card armory-category">
      <h2 id="sonic-stakes">Sonic Repeller Stakes</h2>
      <p class="category-intro">Sonic stakes won't eliminate gophers on their own — don't buy them expecting a standalone fix. What they can do is push gophers out of a specific zone while you're actively trapping. Think of them as a perimeter buffer. I've used them to keep gophers from re-entering a cleared area while I work an adjacent section with traps. Used that way — as a supplement, not a replacement — they earn their spot in the kit.</p>
      <p class="category-intro">For placement strategy, see the <a href="/methods/sonic-stakes">Sonic Repeller Stakes guide</a>.</p>
      <a href="https://amzn.to/4bKpg8v" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="sponsored noopener">Shop Sonic Stakes on Amazon →</a>
      <p class="category-guide-link">Full technique guide: <a href="/methods/sonic-stakes">Sonic Repeller Stakes →</a></p>
    </section>

