    <!-- ============================================================
         FAQ
    ============================================================= -->
    <section class="card">
      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What is the best gopher trap?</summary>
          <p>Victor-style high-tension wire traps (Macabee pattern) are the most reliable for main tunnel intercept work. They're inexpensive, durable, and catch consistently when placed correctly in the main run.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Do I need bait on a gopher trap?</summary>
          <p>Bait isn't required, but a small dab of peanut butter behind the trigger plate increases commitment — the gopher pauses to investigate instead of pushing past the trigger without firing it.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>When should I use gopher gassers instead of traps?</summary>
          <p>Gassers work best when you can't locate the active run in a deep, branching tunnel network. Seal every exit hole before lighting one, or you'll just fumigate your lawn for no effect. See the <a href="/methods/carbon-monoxide">Carbon Monoxide Burrow Treatment guide</a> for full instructions.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Do I need a special probe, or can I use rebar?</summary>
          <p>Rebar from any hardware store does the exact same job as a purpose-built probe. A purpose-built probe just has better ergonomics and handle grip for longer sessions, but the technique is identical.</p>
